
// Playwright Parameterized Tests — Quiz (20 questions, GIFT, English)

::Q1: What is the main benefit of parameterizing tests in Playwright?::
{
=Reducing duplication by running the same logic against many data sets
~Speeding up browser launch times
~Eliminating the need for assertions
~Avoiding the use of fixtures entirely
}

::Q2: Does Playwright provide a built-in test.each API like Jest/Vitest?::
{
=No; idiomatic parameterization uses for...of loops or a small helper
~Yes; use test.each directly from @playwright/test
~Only via third-party plugins
~Yes, but only in UI mode
}

::Q3: Which code pattern best represents idiomatic parameterization?::
{
=Iterating an array of cases with a for...of loop that registers tests
~Creating unique spec files for each case
~Using page.evaluate for dynamic test names
~Duplicating test bodies with different constants
}

::Q4: Which scenarios are good candidates for parameterization?::
{
=Validation rules, boundary values, role-based access, multi-locale
~End-to-end flows that differ completely per case
~Stateful tests that depend on previous tests
~One-off edge cases with unique logic
}

::Q5: What advantage does returning Promise<this> give in fluent page methods during parameterized runs?::
{
=It preserves chaining and subtype correctness across inherited pages
~It disables retries on failure
~It forces tests to run serially
~It clears storageState between cases
}

::Q6: What’s the recommended way to mirror Jest’s test.each naming style if a team prefers it?::
{
=Create a tiny helper that expands cases and substitutes $placeholders in names
~Use expect.each from @playwright/test
~Enable experimental.each in config
~Use projects instead of data arrays
}

::Q7: What is a safe way to trigger field validation for many input cases?::
{
=Fill the field and press Tab (blur) before asserting error state
~Reload the page after each case
~Use waitForTimeout between cases
~Wrap assertions in try/catch without waiting
}

::Q8: What are Projects primarily used for in parameterization?::
{
=Running the same tests across browsers, devices, roles, or environments
~Generating randomized datasets at runtime
~Replacing fixtures entirely
~Serializing test results to CSV
}

::Q9: Which external data source is most convenient for non-engineers to edit?::
{
=JSON or CSV files loaded into tests
~TypeScript modules
~Hard-coded arrays in spec files
~Runtime API calls only
}

::Q10: What is a typical pattern for multi-role access tests?::
{
=Two-dimensional loops over roles and pages with can/cannot assertions
~Duplicating the same test for each role
~One project per test file only
~Relying on console logs for verification
}

::Q11: What is a key rule when loading large test datasets from files?::
{
=Keep data out of the spec file and import/parse it in a utility
~Inline all data in the spec for visibility
~Always transform CSV to XML first
~Prefer screenshots over assertions
}

::Q12: How can you tag parameterized tests for selective execution?::
{
=Attach tag arrays (e.g., ['@smoke']) to each generated test and filter with --grep
~Add comments starting with #smoke in test names
~Set process.env.TAG before running
~Use only project names as filters
}

::Q13: What’s a recommended approach for boundary value generation?::
{
=Programmatically generate cases with helper functions (e.g., numeric/string boundaries)
~Manually create dozens of near-duplicate tests
~Rely on random values without checks
~Only test min and max, skip middle values
}

::Q14: What is a good pattern for API contract testing with parameters?::
{
=Drive tests from an array of {method, path, expectedStatus, expectedShape} and loop
~Use a single test that calls every endpoint sequentially
~Mock all endpoints and skip assertions
~Hard-code only the happy path
}

::Q15: Which approach shares authenticated state most efficiently across many parameterized UI tests?::
{
=Use a storageState file or a worker-scoped authenticated context
~Log in before each parameterized test case
~Share a single Page object across tests
~Set cookies via evaluate() each time
}

::Q16: How do option fixtures help with parameterization?::
{
=They allow per-test overrides via test.use({ option: value }) with defaults
~They disable parallelism for stability
~They force all tests to run in the same project
~They replace the need for environment variables
}

::Q17: What’s the benefit of filtering scenario arrays (e.g., in CI vs local)?::
{
=Run the full matrix in CI while skipping slow/stress cases locally
~Guarantee identical runtime everywhere
~Disable retries automatically
~Prevent tagging from working
}

::Q18: How can you conditionally skip specific parameterized cases?::
{
=Call test.skip(condition, 'reason') inside each generated test
~Throw an error to abort the case
~Use console.log and continue
~Change the test title to include [skipped]
}

::Q19: What is a common anti-pattern when parameterizing UI validation tests?::
{
=Using waitForTimeout between cases instead of relying on auto-waiting
~Triggering validation with blur events
~Using expect(...).toBeVisible()
~Factoring data into arrays
}

::Q20: Which Playwright CLI option runs the same spec across selected projects (e.g., admin and manager)?::
{
=`--project=admin --project=manager`
~`--role=admin,manager`
~`--matrix=admin+manager`
~`--profiles admin manager`
}

